2026-07-13 15:11:30,853 - strands.models.anthropic - DEBUG - request=<{'max_tokens': 8296, 'messages': [{'content': [{'text': "\n            Execute comprehensive defect analysis workflow for defect type 'Color Mismatch' over the last 7 days.\n            \n            Analysis Scope Configuration:\n            - OEE Analysis: Disabled\n            - Downtime Analysis: Disabled\n            - Changeover Analysis: Disabled\n            - Maintenance Correlation: Enabled\n            \n            Execute the following workflow steps:\n            \n            1. **Monitor Phase**: Call Monitor Agent to capture operational data\n               - Focus on Color Mismatch defect occurrences and context\n               - Include enabled analysis areas: Maintenance Correlation\n               - Gather historical patterns and operational context\n            \n            2. **Analysis Phase**: Call Analyzer Agent for root cause analysis\n               - Analyze monitoring data for Color Mismatch root causes\n               - Focus on enabled correlation areas: Maintenance Correlation\n               - Provide statistical confidence and impact assessment\n            \n            3. **Planning Phase**: Call Planner Agent to create action plans\n               - Develop comprehensive improvement plans for Color Mismatch\n               - Address enabled improvement areas: Maintenance Correlation\n               - Include immediate, short-term, and long-term actions\n               - Generate PDF report and capture the filename for email notifications\n            \n            4. **Verification Phase**: Call Verifier Agent to validate findings\n               - Validate analysis results and action plans\n               - Determine notification requirements\n               - Assess need for human expert review\n            \n            5. **Execution Phase**: Call Executor Agent to execute actions\n               - Execute immediate action items\n               - Send email notifications with detailed reports\n               - Include PDF filename from Planner Agent response for email link\n               - Coordinate with manufacturing departments\n            \n            Ensure each agent receives appropriate context from previous phases and respects the analysis scope limitations.\n            \n            IMPORTANT: Extract the PDF filename from the Planner Agent response and pass it to the Executor Agent for email notifications.\n            \n            Compile comprehensive results including all agent outputs and provide executive summary.\n            ", 'type': 'text'}], 'role': 'user'}, {'content': [{'text': "I'll execute the comprehensive defect analysis workflow for Color Mismatch defects over the last 7 days with the specified scope configuration. Let me start by calling the Monitor Agent to capture operational data.", 'type': 'text'}, {'id': 'toolu_01CiFZKKMkCFSdzeEvmJZ6iw', 'input': {'prompt': 'Capture operational data for Color Mismatch defect analysis over the last 7 days. Analysis scope: OEE Analysis disabled, Downtime Analysis disabled, Changeover Analysis disabled, Maintenance Correlation enabled. Focus on Color Mismatch defect occurrences, maintenance-related patterns, and operational context. Provide historical patterns and comprehensive operational data for root cause analysis.'}, 'name': 'call_monitor_agent', 'type': 'tool_use'}], 'role': 'assistant'}, {'content': [{'content': [{'text': 'KEY FINDINGS\n\n- Color Mismatch defects concentrated in Paint and Finish work center (10 of 13 occurrences) on 2026-07-06, with root causes split between Process Variation (4), Machine Calibration (3), Material Defect (2), Operator Error (2), and Design Issue (2) [source: fetch_defect_records, 13 rows, 2026-07-06]\n\n- Machine Pai-32 (Paint Booth) recorded 5 Color Mismatch defects; Machine Pai-31 recorded 3; Quality Control machines (Qua-71, Qua-70) recorded 3 combined, indicating Paint and Finish operations as primary defect source [source: fetch_defect_records, 13 rows, 2026-07-06]\n\n- Afternoon shift (4 defects) and Morning shift (3 defects) show higher Color Mismatch frequency than Night (3) and Weekend shifts (3), with no clear shift-based pattern but temporal clustering around 12:40–14:01 hours [source: fetch_defect_records, 13 rows, 2026-07-06]\n\n- Maintenance-related downtime events (Setup/Changeover, Software Update, Scheduled Maintenance) occurred on Machine Fra-10 (15-min durations) and Paint Booth machines (12-min durations) during 2026-07-06 11:26–13:34, overlapping with Color Mismatch detection window [source: fetch_downtime_events, 189 rows, 2026-07-06 to 2026-07-07]\n\n- No direct temporal correlation between recorded maintenance events and Color Mismatch defects; defects appear post-maintenance completion, suggesting process drift or calibration loss after changeover/software updates [source: fetch_defect_records + fetch_downtime_events, 13 + 189 rows]\n\nSUPPORTING DATA\n\n| Defect Timestamp | Machine | Work Center | Root Cause | Severity | Operator | Shift | Product |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 2026-07-06 14:01:30 | Machine Pai-32 | Paint and Finish | Process Variation | 3 | Christopher Jimenez | Night | eBike T101 |\n| 2026-07-06 13:57:00 | Machine Pai-31 | Paint and Finish | Machine Calibration | 1 | Amanda Barry | Morning | eBike M300 |\n| 2026-07-06 13:35:09 | Machine Pai-32 | Paint and Finish | Design Issue | 3 | Raymond Ford | Morning | eBike T200 |\n| 2026-07-06 13:33:25 | Machine Pai-31 | Paint and Finish | Material Defect | 3 | Melissa Cameron | Afternoon | eBike T101 |\n| 2026-07-06 13:28:15 | Machine Pai-32 | Paint and Finish | Operator Error | 3 | Harold Foster | Afternoon | eBike M300 |\n\nGAPS / MISSING DATA\n\n- Cannot determine if Color Mismatch defects are causally linked to maintenance events; downtime logs show Setup/Changeover and Software Updates on Frame Fabrication (Machine Fra-10) but Paint Booth machines show separate maintenance windows. Temporal proximity exists but causation not available in data.\n- No paint material batch or color specification data available to correlate with Material Defect root causes (2 occurrences).\n- Operator training/certification records not provided; cannot assess if Operator Error (2 occurrences) correlates with recent training gaps or shift transitions.\n- Historical Color Mismatch baseline (prior 30+ days) not captured; cannot determine if 13 defects in 7 days represents anomaly or normal variation.\n\nHANDOFF NOTES\n\n- Escalate Paint and Finish work center (Machines Pai-31, Pai-32) for immediate calibration audit; 10 of 13 defects occurred here with Process Variation and Machine Calibration as dominant root causes.\n- Investigate material supply chain for eBike T101 and T200 products (5 combined defects); cross-reference with Material Defect root causes and batch traceability.\n- Schedule post-maintenance process validation on Paint Booth machines following Setup/Changeover events; current data suggests defects emerge 1–2 hours after maintenance completion, indicating potential recalibration drift.\n', 'type': 'text'}], 'is_error': False, 'tool_use_id': 'toolu_01CiFZKKMkCFSdzeEvmJZ6iw', 'type': 'tool_result'}], 'role': 'user'}, {'content': [{'text': 'Now let me call the Analyzer Agent to perform root cause analysis using the monitoring data:', 'type': 'text'}, {'id': 'toolu_013jSw6kEtkDHW3FTXwMLgA3', 'input': {'prompt': 'Perform root cause analysis for Color Mismatch defects based on monitoring data from last 7 days. Analysis scope: OEE Analysis disabled, Downtime Analysis disabled, Changeover Analysis disabled, Maintenance Correlation enabled. Key data: 13 Color Mismatch defects concentrated in Paint and Finish work center (Machines Pai-31, Pai-32) on 2026-07-06. Root causes identified: Process Variation (4), Machine Calibration (3), Material Defect (2), Operator Error (2), Design Issue (2). Maintenance events (Setup/Changeover, Software Updates) occurred on Paint Booth machines during 11:26-13:34 hours, with defects appearing post-maintenance. Analyze maintenance correlation, process drift patterns, and calibration loss. Provide statistical confidence and impact assessment for enabled scope areas.'}, 'name': 'call_analyzer_agent', 'type': 'tool_use'}], 'role': 'assistant'}, {'content': [{'content': [{'text': "KEY FINDINGS\n\n• Post-maintenance Color Mismatch spike: 13 Color Mismatch defects concentrated on Paint Booth machines (Pai-31, Pai-32) on 2026-07-06 with root causes distributed across Process Variation (4), Machine Calibration (3), Material Defect (2), Operator Error (2), and Design Issue (2). Maintenance events (Setup/Changeover, Software Updates) occurred during 11:26-13:34 hours on Paint Booth machines, with defects appearing post-maintenance window. [source: analyze_quality_defects, 446 rows, 7-day window]\n\n• Maintenance-to-defect correlation: Paint Booth machines show 2 Setup/Changeover events and 2 Software Update events with 12-minute average duration each. Downtime data reveals Material Shortage events (10-20 min) on Paint Booth during Weekend Night shifts (Deanna Miller, 2 events). Post-maintenance process drift is evident with calibration loss as secondary cause. [source: analyze_downtime_correlations, 181 rows; identify_performance_patterns, 199 rows]\n\n• Machine Pai-32 performance degradation: Pai-32 shows AvgOEE 0.42, AvgAvailability 0.72, AvgQuality 0.86 with 9 total orders and 84 total downtime minutes. Operator Melissa Cameron (Afternoon shift) logged 6 orders with 100% completion rate but 56 downtime minutes. Pai-31 shows AvgOEE 0.48, AvgAvailability 0.76, AvgQuality 0.89 with better stability. [source: identify_performance_patterns, 199 rows]\n\n• Calibration loss as primary mechanism: Machine Calibration root cause appears 3 times in Color Mismatch defects (vs. 4 Process Variation). Quality data shows calibration-linked defects across Paint Booth (Pai-30, Pai-31, Pai-32) and Frame Welding (Fra-10). Maintenance events (Software Updates) on Paint Booth during 11:26-13:34 likely triggered recalibration requirement not completed. [source: analyze_quality_defects, 446 rows]\n\n• Process variation dominance post-maintenance: Process Variation root cause (4 instances) exceeds Machine Calibration (3 instances) in Color Mismatch defects, indicating maintenance disrupted process parameters beyond calibration. Afternoon shift (Melissa Cameron, Pai-32) and Weekend Night shift (Deanna Miller, Pai-32) operators both experienced elevated defect rates post-maintenance. [source: analyze_quality_defects, 446 rows]\n\nSUPPORTING DATA\n\n| DefectType | RootCause | MachineName | OperatorName | ShiftName | AvgDefectRate | AvgYieldRate |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Color Mismatch | Process Variation | Machine Pai-32 | Melissa Cameron | Afternoon | 0.04 | 0.94 |\n| Color Mismatch | Process Variation | Machine Pai-32 | Christopher Jimenez | Night | 0.03 | 0.91 |\n| Color Mismatch | Machine Calibration | Machine Pai-31 | Amanda Barry | Morning | 0.02 | 0.88 |\n| Color Mismatch | Operator Error | Machine Pai-32 | Harold Foster | Afternoon | 0.01 | 0.90 |\n| Color Mismatch | Design Issue | Machine Pai-32 | Raymond Ford | Morning | 0.01 | 0.94 |\n| Clear Coat Issue | Machine Calibration | Machine Pai-30 | Samantha Rodriguez | Weekend Night | 0.01 | 0.98 |\n| Paint Run | Machine Calibration | Machine Pai-31 | Anthony Russell | Night | 0.01 | 0.92 |\n| Paint Run | Machine Calibration | Machine Pai-32 | Melissa Cameron | Afternoon | 0.02 | 0.95 |\n\nGAPS / MISSING DATA\n\n• Exact maintenance timestamps not available: User provided 11:26-13:34 window but tool data lacks precise defect timestamps to confirm temporal correlation. Downtime data shows Setup/Changeover and Software Update events but does not link to specific 2026-07-06 date or exact times. Cannot definitively prove causation vs. coincidence.\n\n• Calibration verification data unavailable: No post-maintenance calibration check records returned. Cannot confirm whether calibration was performed, passed, or failed after maintenance window. Pai-31 vs. Pai-32 performance gap (OEE 0.48 vs. 0.42) suggests differential maintenance impact but root cause unconfirmed.\n\n• Material Defect contribution unclear: 2 Material Defect root causes in Color Mismatch defects, but Material Shortage downtime events (10-20 min) occurred on different machines/shifts. Cannot determine if paint material batch issue or machine-specific material handling caused defects.\n\n• Operator skill/training gap: Melissa Cameron (Pai-32, Afternoon) and Deanna Miller (Pai-32, Weekend Night) both show elevated defect rates post-maintenance, but no training records or operator certification data available to assess learning curve post-maintenance.\n\nHANDOFF NOTES\n\n• Immediate action: Verify post-maintenance calibration records for Pai-31 and Pai-32 on 2026-07-06 after 13:34. If calibration was skipped or failed, implement mandatory re-calibration protocol before production restart. Confirm paint material batch consistency during 11:26-13:34 maintenance window.\n\n• Root cause priority: Machine Calibration loss (3 instances) is the highest-confidence root cause for Color Mismatch defects. Process Variation (4 instances) is secondary and likely symptom of incomplete calibration. Recommend recalibration procedure review and operator retraining on post-maintenance verification steps.\n\n• Performance recovery plan: Pai-32 OEE (0.42) lags Pai-31 (0.48) by 12%. Schedule preventive maintenance on Pai-32 with full calibration verification. Monitor Melissa Cameron and Deanna Miller's next 5 shifts on Pai-32 for defect rate normalization. If defects persist, escalate to equipment engineering for sensor/actuator diagnostics.\n", 'type': 'text'}], 'is_error': False, 'tool_use_id': 'toolu_013jSw6kEtkDHW3FTXwMLgA3', 'type': 'tool_result'}], 'role': 'user'}, {'content': [{'text': 'Now let me call the Planner Agent to create action plans and generate the PDF report:', 'type': 'text'}, {'id': 'toolu_01B4TvnU7TxavApqniAv9Pzb', 'input': {'prompt': 'Create comprehensive action plans for Color Mismatch defects based on analysis results. Analysis scope: OEE Analysis disabled, Downtime Analysis disabled, Changeover Analysis disabled, Maintenance Correlation enabled. Key findings: 13 Color Mismatch defects in Paint and Finish work center (Pai-31, Pai-32) on 2026-07-06. Root causes: Process Variation (4), Machine Calibration (3), Material Defect (2), Operator Error (2), Design Issue (2). Maintenance events (Setup/Changeover, Software Updates) during 11:26-13:34 hours preceded defects. Machine Pai-32 shows OEE 0.42, Availability 0.72, Quality 0.86. Develop immediate, short-term, and long-term action plans addressing maintenance correlation and calibration loss. Include resource allocation, timelines, and success metrics. Generate comprehensive PDF report with filename and include all analysis details within enabled scope.'}, 'name': 'call_planner_agent', 'type': 'tool_use'}], 'role': 'assistant'}, {'content': [{'content': [{'text': "## Action Plans Created Successfully\n\nI have developed comprehensive action plans for the Color Mismatch defects and generated a detailed PDF report. Here's the summary:\n\n### KEY FINDINGS\n\n- **13 Color Mismatch defects** concentrated in Paint work center (Pai-31, Pai-32) on 2026-07-06 [source: Maintenance Correlation Analysis, 13 defects]\n- **Maintenance-Quality Correlation Confirmed**: Setup/Changeover and Software Updates during 11:26-13:34 hours directly preceded all defects [source: Maintenance Correlation Analysis, 100% correlation]\n- **Process Variation (4 defects, 31%)** is dominant root cause, followed by Machine Calibration loss (3 defects, 23%) [source: Root Cause Analysis, 13 defects]\n- **Pai-32 Critical Performance Gap**: OEE 0.42, Availability 0.72 (28% downtime), Quality 0.86 [source: Machine Performance Metrics, Pai-32 only]\n- **Secondary Issues**: Material Defect (2 defects) and Design Issue (2 defects) require supplier audit and design review [source: Root Cause Distribution, 13 defects]\n\n### SUPPORTING DATA\n\n| Root Cause | Defect Count | Percentage | Primary Machine | Action Priority |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Process Variation | 4 | 31% | Pai-31/Pai-32 | Immediate - SPC |\n| Machine Calibration | 3 | 23% | Pai-32 | Immediate - Calibration |\n| Material Defect | 2 | 15% | Pai-31/Pai-32 | Short-term - Supplier |\n| Operator Error | 2 | 15% | Pai-31/Pai-32 | Immediate - Retraining |\n| Design Issue | 2 | 15% | Pai-31/Pai-32 | Short-term - Review |\n| OEE (Pai-32) | 0.42 | Target ≥0.85 | Gap: -0.43 | Critical |\n| Availability (Pai-32) | 0.72 | Target ≥0.90 | Gap: -0.18 | Critical |\n| Quality (Pai-32) | 0.86 | Target ≥0.95 | Gap: -0.09 | High |\n\n### GAPS / MISSING DATA\n\n- **OEE Analysis disabled**: Cannot determine Performance/Quality breakdown for Pai-31; only Pai-32 metrics available. Limits comparison of both machines' calibration sensitivity.\n- **Downtime Analysis disabled**: Cannot identify specific causes of Pai-32's 28% availability loss (maintenance, equipment failure, or scheduling). Prevents targeted availability improvement strategy.\n- **Changeover Analysis disabled**: Cannot assess if Setup/Changeover activities involved product changes triggering calibration loss. Limits changeover-specific quality procedure evaluation.\n- **Material batch traceability missing**: Cannot confirm if Material Defect (2 defects) originated from single batch or multiple suppliers. Supplier audit scope may be incomplete.\n- **Design specification tolerances missing**: Cannot assess if Design Issue reflects unachievable specifications or process capability gap. Design review may recommend unnecessary changes.\n\n### HANDOFF NOTES\n\n- **PDF Report Generated**: `MES_Analysis_Report_20260713_151118.pdf` (10.5 KB) contains executive summary, detailed root cause analysis, prioritized action plans with timelines, resource allocation ($180K total 12-month investment, 14.5 FTE), and success metrics. Ready for distribution to manufacturing leadership.\n- **Immediate Priority**: Execute Emergency Machine Calibration Recovery (0-7 days) and Maintenance Event Documentation (0-14 days) to prevent recurrence of maintenance-induced defects. Target: zero color mismatch defects within 48 hours post-maintenance.\n- **Resource Commitment Required**: 3.5 FTE immediate, 7 FTE short-term (1-3 months), 4 FTE long-term (3-12 months). Capital investment phased: $15K immediate, $45K short-term, $120K long-term. Success metrics: Pai-32 OEE 0.42→≥0.65, Availability 0.72→≥0.90, defect elimination within 90 days.\n", 'type': 'text'}], 'is_error': False, 'tool_use_id': 'toolu_01B4TvnU7TxavApqniAv9Pzb', 'type': 'tool_result'}], 'role': 'user'}], 'model': 'claude-haiku-4-5-20251001', 'tools': [{'name': 'call_monitor_agent', 'description': 'Call the Monitor Agent to capture operational data', 'input_schema': {'properties': {'prompt': {'description': 'Parameter prompt', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['prompt'], 'type': 'object'}}, {'name': 'call_analyzer_agent', 'description': 'Call the Analyzer Agent to perform root cause analysis', 'input_schema': {'properties': {'prompt': {'description': 'Parameter prompt', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['prompt'], 'type': 'object'}}, {'name': 'call_planner_agent', 'description': 'Call the Planner Agent to create action plans', 'input_schema': {'properties': {'prompt': {'description': 'Parameter prompt', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['prompt'], 'type': 'object'}}, {'name': 'call_verifier_agent', 'description': 'Call the Verifier Agent to validate findings', 'input_schema': {'properties': {'prompt': {'description': 'Parameter prompt', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['prompt'], 'type': 'object'}}, {'name': 'call_executor_agent', 'description': '"Call the Executor Agent to execute plans and send notifications', 'input_schema': {'properties': {'prompt': {'description': 'Parameter prompt', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['prompt'], 'type': 'object'}}], 'system': 'You are the Supervisor Agent for the Manufacturing Execution System (MES) AI workflow.\n\nYour primary responsibility is to orchestrate the complete defect analysis workflow by coordinating five specialized agents:\n\n1. **Monitor Agent**: Captures operational data and contextualizes manufacturing events\n2. **Analyzer Agent**: Performs root cause analysis and identifies correlations\n3. **Planner Agent**: Creates actionable improvement plans and generates reports and return PDF File Name\n4. **Verifier Agent**: Validates findings and manages human validation\n5. **Executor Agent**: Executes action plans and sends email notifications\n\n**Workflow Process:**\n1. Receive defect analysis request with defect type, time period, and analysis scope parameters\n2. Call Monitor Agent to capture comprehensive operational data based on enabled scope\n3. Call Analyzer Agent to perform root cause analysis using monitoring data and scope\n4. Call Planner Agent to create action plans based on analysis results and scope\n5. Call Verifier Agent to validate findings within scope\n6. Call Executor Agent to pass PDF file Name, execute immediate actions and send email notifications with PDF link in format(https://dfmw0zqekwl4n.cloudfront.net/proxy/8501/pdf=pdf_filename.pdf?pdf=pdf_filename.pdf)\n7. Compile complete analysis results with all agent outputs\n\n**Analysis Scope Parameters:**\n- include_oee: Enable/disable OEE performance analysis\n- include_downtime: Enable/disable downtime and stoppages analysis\n- include_changeover: Enable/disable batch changeover analysis\n- include_maintenance: Enable/disable maintenance correlation analysis\n\n**Key Responsibilities:**\n- Ensure proper data flow between agents with scope considerations\n- Maintain analysis context throughout the workflow\n- Coordinate timing and sequencing of agent activities\n- Compile comprehensive results from all agents\n- Handle error recovery and workflow continuity\n- Provide executive summary of complete analysis\n- Respect analysis scope limitations and focus areas\n- Use Executor Agent for one email notification and action execution\n- Pass PDF filename from Planner Agent to Executor Agent for email notifications\n\n**Critical Workflow Note:**\nWhen calling the Planner Agent, extract the PDF filename from the response and pass it to the Executor Agent when calling for email notifications. This ensures the PDF link is included in the email body.\n\n**Output Format:**\nAlways return a structured analysis result containing:\n- Defect type and analysis parameters including scope settings\n- Monitoring results with operational context within enabled scope\n- Root cause analysis with HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW certainty ratings for enabled areas\n- Action plans with timelines and resources for enabled scope\n- Verification results with validation status\n- Execution results with notification status\n- Executive summary with key findings and recommendations\n\nFocus on ensuring each agent receives appropriate context and scope parameters, and that the complete workflow produces actionable, validated insights for manufacturing quality improvement within the specified analysis scope. All email notifications should be handled through the Executor Agent with proper PDF filename passing.\n\n=== OUTPUT RULES (mandatory) ===\n- No emoji, no ASCII-art charts, no decorative separators.\n- Report only numbers that appear in tool results or subagent reports.\n  Never compute totals, percentages, correlations, confidence\n  percentages, or dollar amounts yourself. If a number was not\n  returned by a tool, write "not available in data" instead.\n- Never compare values against industry standards, benchmarks,\n  "world-class" figures, or "required" durations unless those values\n  appear in tool results.\n- Express certainty only as HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW with a one-line reason.\n', 'temperature': 0.2}>
